The goal you landed on
When a test runs and the stored (DB) primary locator no longer works because the page changed, the system should: heal the element via the existing fallback chain, then recompute the element's proper primary from the now-located element, and if that recomputed primary differs from what's stored, update the DB with the new primary plus a fresh smart-locator bundle and meta. If the stored primary still works, leave everything alone.
That's "compare page vs DB primary, update if changed" — done at heal time, because that's the only moment you have a working handle on the element to recompute from.
File 1 — selfHealing.ts
Added: PRIMARY_PRIORITY + pickBestPrimary. A ranked list (role, testId, label, placeholder, text, alt, title, css, xpath) and a function that returns the highest-priority locator present in a bundle. This is "what's the best locator this element currently supports."
Added: detectStrategy. Reads a primary string and tells you which getBy* strategy it uses (e.g. getByRole(...) → 'role'). Returns null for css/xpath/raw. This is how you know what kind of locator the old primary was.
Added: pickMatchingPrimary. The heart of your final decision. Given the regenerated bundle and the old primary string, it tries to keep the same strategy the old primary used (just with a refreshed value) — so a getByRole element stays a getByRole locator. Only if that strategy no longer exists on the page does it fall back to pickBestPrimary. This is what makes the update a surgical repair of the existing primary rather than swapping in whatever random locator happened to heal it.
Added: recomputeBundleFromElement. The single entry point the engine calls. Given a working (healed) locator, it does one extractElementMeta call, regenerates the full smart bundle from that meta, picks the new primary via pickMatchingPrimary, and returns { primary, smartLocators, meta } — all three derived from the same extraction, so they're internally consistent (the meta.matchIndex matches the bundle it was generated with).
Fixed (two bugs in your existing generateSmartLocators): the CSS scoped-fallback and XPath ancestor-fallback branches previously computed a value and then threw it away (if (!locators.css) { await generateScopedCss(...) } with no assignment). Now those results are assigned through. This matters because the recompute path runs this same function — if those fallbacks silently returned nothing, an element that only had a scoped-CSS or ancestor-XPath locator would recompute to an empty bundle and the refresh would no-op.
File 2 — elementRepo.ts
Added: refreshElementLocators. A focused UPDATE that writes only primary_locator, smart_locators, and meta (plus updated_at). It deliberately does not touch screenshots, DOM, or page_url — that's the "update nothing else" you specified. It's separate from saveElement on purpose: saveElement is a 9-column upsert for first-time capture; this is a surgical 3-column update for refreshes. meta is written alongside smart_locators so matchIndex stays in sync (the AI-disambiguation path depends on it).
saveElement and getElement are unchanged.
File 3 — fallbackEngine.ts
Changed imports: added refreshElementLocators to the elementRepo import, and recomputeBundleFromElement from selfHealing.
Added: refreshStaleElement helper (above findWithFallback). This holds comparison #2 — the string comparison. It calls recomputeBundleFromElement on the healed locator, compares the recomputed primary against the stored DB primary, and:

if they're equal → does nothing (no redundant write),
if different → calls refreshElementLocators to update the DB.

It's wrapped in try/catch so a refresh failure can never break the heal itself — promotion is best-effort, the test still passes on the healed locator.
Added: two call sites. refreshStaleElement(...) is called on the smart-tier success branch (passing built) and the AI-tier success branch (passing aiLocator), each right after the existing saveHealingLog, before the return. Both pass dbPrimaryLocatorStr (the stored primary from STEP 1) as the comparison baseline.
Unchanged but now meaningful: STEP 1 is comparison #1. It already tests whether the stored DB primary still resolves on the page. If it does (page == DB), it returns immediately and no refresh runs — that's your "if same, leave it." No refresh on the catch/failure branch either, since nothing was located.
So the two comparisons are: STEP 1 catches "still works" by resolution (cheap, up front); refreshStaleElement catches "changed, here's the new one" by string compare (after healing gives you a handle to recompute from).
