File 5 — refreshElement.nojest.spec.ts (new test)
A Playwright-Test-only spec (no jest) that monkeypatches the DB functions on the imported module objects, records calls to refreshElementLocators, and asserts three behaviors: db-primary-resolves → no refresh; broken-primary-heals → refresh with the new primary still a getByRole (strategy preserved) and primary+smart+meta written together; db-primary-agrees → no write. I verified the monkeypatch genuinely intercepts the engine's internal call under CommonJS.
The end-to-end flow you built
First run: element captured normally (unchanged). Later run, page has changed: the POM locator fails → findWithFallback runs → STEP 1's stored primary also fails (comparison #1 says "changed") → smart or AI tier locates the element → refreshStaleElement recomputes the best primary from that located element, preserving the old strategy → compares to stored (comparison #2) → writes primary + smart_locators + meta if different. Next run: STEP 1 tries the refreshed primary, it works, the chain self-shortens — and the smart locators behind it are current too, so the next break has a fresh fallback set.
One honest caveat to keep in mind: the recompute is only as good as what generateSmartLocators can find on the changed page. If the element's strategy genuinely disappeared (e.g. it lost its role), pickMatchingPrimary falls back to best-available rather than preserving strategy — which is the correct behavior, but means "strategy preserved" is a best-effort guarantee, not absolute.
